Jinzhou 510K
Card game

Jinzhou Five-Ten-King is a popular four-player competitive card game in the Western Liaoning Region of China, belonging to the team-based board and card game category. The core of the game revolves around capturing point cards, using two decks of playing cards (totaling 108 cards). Teams compete to accumulate 200 card points (a 5 is worth 5 points, a 10 or a King is worth 10 points each).
The game begins with the player holding the Ace of Hearts making the first play. When taking turns to play cards, a player must beat the card combination played by the previous player. If no one can beat the played cards for three consecutive rounds, the player who played them claims the current round's points. A team wins only when all its members have played all their cards; members who have not played their cards will have their hand's point value deducted. The final victory margin is calculated by dividing the point difference by 10. Special card combinations include Straights, Sequences of Pairs, Five-Ten-King, and various "Cannon" types. Among these, the Octuple Cannon is the highest-ranking combination, and the strength of a Pure Five-Ten-King is determined by its suit. The game's rules emphasize teamwork and strategic card combination play.
